<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-11-07T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-11-07T19:00:00-05:00" n="541" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d541">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">812.543 Palmolive Co./5: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Mexico</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Morrow</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-11-07T19:00:00-05:00">November 7, 1929—7
                                p.m.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>505. Your 351, November 5, 6 p.m. Department is clearly of opinion that
                            under provisions article 2, Washington Convention, any corporation
                            organized under laws of a country party to that convention and owning a
                            trade mark registered in the United States would be permitted to sue in
                            United States Courts for infringement of such trade mark. See <hi rend="italic">The French Republic</hi> v. <hi rend="italic">Saratoga
                                Vichy Spring Co.</hi>, 191 U.S. 427; and <hi rend="italic">Baglin</hi> v. <hi rend="italic">Cusenier Company</hi>, 221 U. S.
                            580.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Stimson</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>